                          Art


        Had it not been for its explosion of great art, the Renai-

ssance would surely not seem as splendid as it does. Suddenly, large

sums of money were being paid out to buy objects of beauty; art to
                                        51
enrich life became the order of the day.


        During the Middle Ages, painting, sculpture, and architecture

were thought of as crafts. The powerful trade guilds who ordered 

works of art used standard pattern books for guidance, and gave 

strict instructions to the craftsmen they employed. Most earned 

their liaing decorating churches, which ment working on biblical 

scenes and episodes from the lives of the saints. The conservationims

of the church had prevented them from experimenting; anything new was

likely to be rbanded heresy Gradually, however, the humansts taught 

a more sensual sense of beauty; a frank admiration for the human body

-male or female, preferably nude- permeated the education classes.
                                                                52,53,54
The humanists introduced their pagan motives into Christian art.


                       Architecture


        Before the Renaissance, the architecture of Italy had been

influenced by Gothic, Romanesque, Greek, and Byzantine styles. Now

the humanists turned architectural vision to the ruin of Rome. To

build again in the classic style of Ancient Rome became the dream and

passion of men like Brunelleschi, Alberti, Michelozzo, Michaelangelo,  
            55
and Raphael.   

        The new churches and houses of the Renaissance were molded

largely on the buildings of Ancient Rome.  They had rounded arches

and broad windows which made their interiors light.  The decorations
                                          56
were also copied from classical buildings.  

        The Florentine architect Brunelleschi had traveled between 

Rome and Florence for about 12 years, examining classical architecture,

studying mathematics, and making clocks in his spare time to earn 

some money.  He spent hours crawling over the roofs of Roman buildings,

and even removed the tiles to find out more about the techniques the 
            57            
Romans used.


        Brunelleschi used what he had learned about Roman building 

methods in his design for the great dome of Santa Maria del Fiore

cathedral in Florence. The builders had come to a halt, since no one

knew how to build a dome on the vast scale that was needed. He pur-

suaded the people of Florence to use his design. The dome was 82 
                                                     58,59
meters high - the largest dome anyone had ever built. 


        The new homes in Florence were designed to be delightful 

places to live in. In 1490 Lorenzo de' Medici turned one of his coun-

try houses into a villa with ideas from a Greek temple. Gardens for

the new villa were laid out according to classical styles. Flower 

beds and paths were arranged to form regular patterns which were based

on squares and circles. The gardens were decorated with fountains and
                                       60
statues following the classical styles. 


                        Painting


        Before the Renaissance, painting in Italy was mostly influ-

enced by the Byzantine style from the eastern Mediterranean. Religion 

was the cheif theme. Often tall, stern-faced saints and angels were 

shown against flat gold backgrounds. there was little feeling of dis-

tance between the figures, and it didn't seem to matter if they were 

all the wrong size in relation to another.


        Around 1300 a painter called Giotto broke away from this style.

He tried to paint more realistically, and with human expressions. He

tried to make his pictures look solid and to set them against real-

looking backgrounds. 


        At the beginning of the 15th century artists began to com-

bine Giotto's ideas with those of classical times. The Ancient Romans

thought that proportion was very important, and the Renaissance

artists began to work out rules for their paintings. Objects and 

figures were based on the most perfect proportions. The head, for

instance, was one-seventh the length of the body.


        Artists were particularly intersted in the problem of per-

spective, which meant making the objects in the background of a pic-

ture seem the right size and shape compared with the objects in the

front. Brunelleschi noticed that the parallel lines of green and white

marble on the walls of the baptistry in Florence seemed to closer

together the farther away from him they were. Using his observations

artists worked out rules for showing perspective in their pictures.


        Masaccio was one of the first artists to follow Brunelleschi's

theories. He also managed to make his pictures very solid, by noticing

how light fell on objects and carefully painting in the shadows.

Masaccio died in 1428 but his ideas were used by other artists in 

Florence.


        Masaccio's paintings are mostly of religous subjects, but

the painters who followed him often illustrated classical stories or

painted portraits of rich people.Religous subjects remained common,

although sometimes when an artist like Raphael painted a portrait of

the Virgin Mary, it was really a portrait of his own mistress. 


        The "Mona Lisa", by Leonardo da Vinci is probably the most

famous of all paintings. Leonardo finished very few paintings since 

he was often busy working as an engineer and inventor. Some of his 

paintings have not lasted well because he experimented with different

kinds of paint. He used tempra instead of fresco for a vast wall

painting of the Last Supper, and even in his own lifetime paint was

flaking off the wall. Leonardo da Vinci was one of the most brilliant

men who has ever lived. He was both an artist and a scientist. At 

the time art and science were not thought of as two subjects, but as

one. Both depended on an accurate observation and close measurement

of the world. Leonardo had the imagination of a great artist, and a

scientists knowledge of how things work. He became a brilliant 

inventor. He designed a war machine on wheels, which was protected

by armor like a tank.He drew scetches of machines with which he bel-

ieved men could fly. He invented the idea of a parachute,and of 

explosive shells fired by a cannon. It was centuries before other
                                                            
scientists had these ideas and put them into practice. After Leonardos

death many of his ideas remained in his notebooks, unpublished and

unknown. But one invention which Leonerdo did put to work was a new

design for a lock gate, to control the flow of water in rivers and

canals. This design is still in use today. This genius of the Renais-

was truly a man for all ages.


        Another Renaissance artist skilled at a number of activities

was Michelangelo. as well as being a great sculptor he was a good
architect, a poet,and one of the finest painters who ever lived. His

most famous work as a painter is the series of religious scenes on

the huse ceiling of the Sistine Chapel in Rome. This work was begun

in 1508, and shows episodes from the Book of Genesis, including the

Creation of Man. The area which Micelangelo had to decorate was over

900 square meters. The fresco technique, which was needed for the 

painting, was something in which he had little practice.  However he 

carried out the project almost singlehanded and nearly blinded himself

as a result, because he had to work much of the time on his back fac_

ing the ceiling. After more than four years of work the public was

to see a work of art so profound in ideas that it can be said never

to have been surpassed before or since.

        In Michaelangelo, we see the triumph of all that artists had

been striving for during the past century: Christian ideas expressed
 
in classical grandeur;difficult technical problems beautifully solved;

challenges met; status established and honor won.    


                        


                     


         




